As of 2007, there are two dams built on the Yangtze river: Three Gorges Dam and [[Gezhouba Dam]] with a third one, [[Xiluodu Dam]] under construction. More dams are in planning stage, such as Wudongde, Baihetan, and Xiangjiaba.

==Tributaries==
[[Image:Yangzi river ship yard on river bank.jpg|300px|thumb|right|A shipyard on the banks of the Yangtze building commercial river freight boats]]

The Yangtze River has over 700 [[tributaries]]. The major tributaries (listed from upstream to downstream) with the locations of where they join the Yangtze are:
*[[Yalong River]] (Yunnan Province)
*[[Min River (Sichuan)|Min River]] ([[Yibin]], Sichuan Province)
*[[Jialing River]] ([[Chongqing]])
*[[Wu River (Yangtze River tributary)|Wu Jiang]]
*[[Qing Jiang]] ([[Yidu, Hubei|Yidu]], Hubei Province)
*[[Yuan River]] 
*[[Zi Shui]]
*[[Xiang River]]([[Yueyang]], Hunan)
*[[Han River (Hanshui)|Han River]] ([[Wuhan]], Hubei)
*[[Gan River (Jiangxi)|Gan River]] (near [[Jiujiang]], Jiangxi Province.)

==Protected areas==
*[[Sanjiangyuan National Nature Reserve|Sanjiangyuan (&quot;Three Rivers' Sources&quot;) National Nature Reserve]] in [[Qinghai]]
*[[Three Parallel Rivers of Yunnan]]

==Wildlife==
The Yangtze is home to at least three critically endangered species: The [[Chinese Alligator]], the [[Finless Porpoise]] and the [[Chinese Paddlefish]].  (This is the only other place besides the U.S. that is native to an alligator species.)  The [[Finless Porpoise]] were counted in 2010 to be 1000 exemplars. More species have become extinct in the Yangtze than in any other river in China.{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}} This is due to commercial use of the river coupled with tourism and pollution. In December 2006, the [[Baiji]] (Chinese River Dolphin) was declared [[functional extinction|functionally extinct]] after an extensive search of the river revealed no signs of the dolphin's inhabitance; however, one was sighted soon after.&lt;ref&gt;[http://sciencemode.com/2007/09/02/river-dolphin-thought-to-be-extinct-spotted-again-in-china/ ScienceMode » River Dolphin Thought to be Extinct Spotted Again in China]&lt;/ref&gt;

==Miscellanea==
*[[Cheung Kong Holdings]], from the [[Yue Chinese|Cantonese]] form of Chang Jiang and named after the river, is the name of the [[holding company]] controlled by [[Li Ka-Shing]], one of Asia's richest [[tycoon]]s.
*In 2004 [[Martin Strel]] from [[Slovenia]] swam the river from the [[Tiger Leaping Gorge]] to [[Shanghai]] ({{convert|4600|km|mi|abbr=on|lk=off}}.
*In 1342 the Yangtze River in Jiangsu Province was reported to have run dry. Water completely disappeared for a day and the riverbed became visible. This event occurred again on January 13, 1954.&lt;ref name=yangtzedry&gt;According to p. 140 of the 986th edition of Australian ''Chinese Daily'' magazine published on 18 August 2007.&lt;/ref&gt;
*The river was first rafted from source to mouth in 1986 by all-Chinese teams attempting to beat a Sino-American team to the first descent. Ten of the rafters drowned. The event was widely followed by the Chinese press, and became a source of national pride.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.shangri-la-river-expeditions.com/1stdes/yangtze/yangtzesummary.html Yangtze River Pictures&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;]&lt;/ref&gt;
*As the Yangtze is undergoing a transformation due to the Three Gorges Dam, Canadian documentary filmmaker Yung Chang made an award-winning documentary called [http://www.zeitgeistfilms.com/film.php?directoryname=uptheyangtze Up the Yangtze].

