'''Cantor Fitzgerald L.P.''' is a global [[financial services]] firm specializing in [[Bond (finance)|bond trading]].

The firm is one of twenty [[primary dealers]] who trade [[Treasury security|U.S. government securities]] directly with the [[Federal Reserve Bank of New York]],&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[http://www.newyorkfed.org/markets/pridealers_current.html Primary Dealers List]&quot;, Federal Reserve Bank of New York&lt;/ref&gt; and is also involved in [[investment banking]], [[asset management]], [[market data]], and [[brokerage]] services.

Now headquartered in [[Midtown Manhattan]], [[New York City]],&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[http://www.cantor.com/contact/location Locations].&quot; Cantor Fitzgerald. Retrieved on October 4, 2009.&lt;/ref&gt; it was formerly based in the [[World Trade Center]] - and was particularly hard hit by the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]].

==September 11, 2001 attacks==
[[File:Wtc arial march2001.jpg|thumb|[[World Trade Center|One World Trade Center]], the building with the antenna to the left, included the corporate headquarters of Cantor Fitzgerald]]
Cantor Fitzgerald's corporate headquarters and New York City office,&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[http://web.archive.org/web/20000304012316/www.cantor.com/locations.htm office locations].&quot; Cantor Fitzgerald. March 4, 2000. Retrieved on October 4, 2009.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[http://web.archive.org/web/20010809041147/http://www.cantor.com/locations.htm office locations].&quot; Cantor Fitzgerald. August 9, 2001. Retrieved on October 4, 2009.&lt;/ref&gt; on the 101st-105th floors of [[World Trade Center|One World Trade Center]] in [[Lower Manhattan]] (2-6 floors above the impact zone of a [[American Airlines Flight 11|hijacked airliner]]), were destroyed during the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]]. Cantor Fitzgerald lost 658 employees (all of the employees in the office at the time of the attacks), or about two-thirds of its workforce, considerably more than any other of the [[List of World Trade Center tenants|World Trade Center tenants]] or the [[New York City Police Department]] and [[New York City Fire Department]]. The company was able to bring its trading markets back online within a week, and [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] and [[chairman]] Howard Lutnick, whose brother was among those killed, vowed to keep the company alive. 

On September 19, Cantor Fitzgerald made a pledge to distribute 25 percent of the firm's profits for the next five years, and committed to paying for ten years of health care, for the benefit of the families of its 658 former Cantor Fitzgerald, eSpeed, and TradeSpark employees (profits which would otherwise have been distributed to the Cantor Fitzgerald [[Partnership|partners]]).&lt;ref name=&quot;msnbc&quot;&gt;http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/39038466/ns/us_news-911_nine_years_later/ns/us_news-911_nine_years_later?GT1=43001&lt;/ref&gt; In 2006 the company completed its promise, having paid a total of $180&amp;nbsp;million&lt;ref name=&quot;msnbc&quot; /&gt; (and an additional $17&amp;nbsp;million from a relief fund run by Lutnick's sister, Edie).{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}}

Before the attacks, Cantor handled about one-quarter of the daily transactions in the multi-trillion dollar [[treasury security]] market. Cantor has since rebuilt its [[infrastructure]] and now has its headquarters in [[midtown Manhattan]]. The company's effort to regain its footing is the subject of [[Tom Barbash]]'s 2003 book ''On Top of the World: Cantor Fitzgerald, Howard Lutnick, and 9/11: A Story of Loss and Renewal''.

On September 2, 2004, Cantor filed a [[Lawsuit|civil lawsuit]] against the [[Saudi Arabia|Kingdom of Saudi Arabia]], one of a number of organizations to do so.&lt;ref&gt;[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/3646548.stm WTC agency sues Saudis over 9/11], BBC News Online, 11th September 2004&lt;/ref&gt; It was later joined in the suit by the [[Port Authority of New York]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.law.com/jsp/article.jsp?id=1094073283938 Port Authority to Join Suit Against Saudi Arabia Over 9/11 Attack], Associated Press, 13th September 2004&lt;/ref&gt;

Immediately after the first attack, at approximately 8:46:46&amp;nbsp;AM, six seconds after the first plane hit the tower, a Goldman Sachs server sent out an alert page stating that a [[Goldman Sachs]] trading system server had gone offline because it was unable to interface with a Cantor server.&lt;ref&gt;[http://911.wikileaks.org/files/messages_2001_09_11-08_45_2001_09_11-08_49.html#407 2001-09-11 08:46:46 Arch [1612975&amp;#93; D ALPHA]&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Egads! Confidential 9/11 Pager Messages Disclosed|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/blogs/2009/11/25/taking_liberties/entry5770280.shtml|last=McCullagh|first=Declan|date=2009-11-25|work=Taking Liberties|publisher=CBS News Blogs|accessdate=2009-11-28|archivedate=2009-11-28|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5ldFgVaDM}}&lt;/ref&gt;

