* [[Ground improvements at English football Stadia]]

===International Matches===
In recent years, Craven Cottage has hosted several International Friendly matches, including the [[Republic of Ireland national football team]] who recently played Colombia and Nigeria there in May 2008 and May 2009 respectively.
The [[Korea Republic national football team]] have also used the ground twice in recent years for international friendlies, first against Greece in February 2007 and then against Serbia in November 2009.
On 17 November 2007 Australia beat Nigeria 1–0 in an international friendly at Craven Cottage.
&lt;ref&gt;Sky Sports Match Commentary http://www.skysports.com/football/match_commentary/0,19764,11065_2962689,00.html and http://www.skysports.com/football/match_facts/0,,11065_2917906,00.html&lt;/ref&gt;
In 26 May 2011, Crave Cottage hosted the game of [[2011 UEFA Women's Champions League Final]] between [[Olympique Lyonnais Féminin|Lyon]] and [[1. FFC Turbine Potsdam|Potsdam]].

===Trivia===
* [[Harlequins Rugby League#Fulham Rugby League Club|Fulham Rugby League Club]] played at Craven Cottage between 1980 and 1984, hosting their largest attendance. The ground has also hosted Oxbridge varsity matches in rugby and football.
[[Image:Michael-Jackson-statue-Fulham.jpg|300px - 577769.jpg|thumb|right|statue of [[Michael Jackson]]]]
* The ground has hosted the most [[Australia national association football team|Socceroo]] matches outside of [[Australia]] and was one of the pioneers in hosting (neutral) international friendlies.
* Fulham were the last team to have standing accommodation in the [[Premier League]], as Craven Cottage included terraces in the [[2001-02 in English football|2001–02 season]] – eight years after the [[Taylor Report]] outlawed terraces at this level.
*The original Craven Cottage site was covered in woodlands. One [[Platanus|plane tree]] survives today in a corner of the Putney End, the sole tree to be found in any British senior football stadium.
*On 3 April 2011, Fulham unveiled a statue of [[Michael Jackson]] outside the stadium before its match with Blackpool. The singer, who died in 2009, attended a Fulham match once and was friends with club chairman [[Mohamed Al-Fayed]], who commissioned the statue.&lt;ref&gt;ESPN, &quot;Michael Jackson statue unveiled.&quot; http://espn.go.com/sports/soccer/news/_/id/6286197/statue-michael-jackson-unveiled-fulham-home-stadium&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;http://sportshaze.com/england/english-premier-league/english-premier-league-fans-can-go-to-hell-says-fulham-owner-mohamed-al-fayed-2659&lt;/ref&gt;

